The sad ANEMONE

                           Anemone. l. 316. Many males, many females. Pliny says this flower never opens its petals but when the wind blows; whence its name; it has properly no calix, but two or three sets of petals, three in each set, which are folded over the stamens and pistil in a singular and beautiful manner, and differs also from ranunculus in not having a melliferous pore on the claw of each petal.
